Mijn naam is Anouk en ik ben UGC-creator binnen beauty, fashion, mama(zwanger) & lifestyle.

Ik help merken met het maken van authentieke, converterende content die direct inzetbaar is voor Instagram, TikTok en advertenties.

Wat ik aanbied: 

‚Ä¢ UGC video‚Äôs (reels / TikTok / ads)

‚Ä¢ Professionele productfoto‚Äôs

‚Ä¢ Content die vertrouwen opbouwt bij de doelgroep

‚Ä¢ Snelle levering en duidelijke afspraken

Samenwerkingen zijn mogelijk per opdracht of structureel (wekelijks/maandelijks).

Waarom merken voor mij kiezen: 

- Professionele uitstraling

- Ervaring binnen lifestyle & mama-doelgroepen

- Content met focus op zichtbaarheid en conversie

- Betrouwbare communicatie

Portfolio: https://linktr.ee/anoukterband

üì© Interesse? Stuur gerust een berichtje of reageer onder me post, dan denk ik graag met je mee voor doelgroep & merk! Ideaal voor merken die serieus willen groeien met UGC.

Liefs Anouk

Die neue Essenz-Methode ist nicht einfach eine weitere Schauspieltechnik. 

 

Die Methode basiert auf:
* 15+ Jahren Casting- & Kamera-Erfahrung
* Coaching von hunderten Darstellern
* Erfolgen, die Menschen in Filme, Serien, Preise & Chart-Songs gebracht haben

 

Sie vereint alles, was du wirklich brauchst um vor der Kamera zu strahlen. 

Strukturiert, gegliedert und direkt umsetzbar. 

 

Im Workshop lernst du:

‚úî wie du Energie vor der Kamera aufbaust

‚úî wie du ber√ºhrst statt spielst

‚úî wie du Blockaden l√∂st

‚úî wie du dich authentisch zeigst

‚úî wie du deine Wirkung nutzt, um Caster und Regisseure WIRKLICH zu √ºberzeugen. 

 

üìÜ **Early Bird gilt nur noch bis 10.12, 23:59 Uhr. **

Der g√ºnstigste Preis, den es bei uns je f√ºr einen Workshop geben wird ;-)

+++EXKLUSIVER SCHAUSPIEL-WORKSHOP f√ºr QUEREINSTEIGER*INNEN+++

(NUR NOCH 3 FREIE PL√ÑTZE! - Stand: 06.12.2025)

#schauspielworkshop #quereinsteiger #schauspielquereinsteiger #quereinsteigerworkshop #cameraacting #arbeitsworkshop #showreel #aboutme #film #tv #exklusiv #engelspostmanagement

Aufgrund der gro√üen Nachfrage veranstalte ich im JANUAR 2026 (09.-11.01.+16.-18.01.2026 / 2 WE) einen EXKLUSIVEN, 6-T√ÑGIGEN Schauspiel-Workshop f√ºr QUEREINSTEIGER*INNEN. Die Inhalte k√∂nnt Ihr dem Flyer entnehmen. 

Quereinsteiger*innen haben wenig M√∂glichkeiten auf dem deutschen Markt, weshalb ich mich dazu entschieden habe, ein sinnvolles, n√ºtzliches Angebot auf den Markt zu bringen. 

Es handelt sich um einen PRAXISORIENTIERTEN Workshop, was bedeutet, in welchem mit den Teilnehmenden an der Performance gearbeitet wird, u. a. durch Szenenarbeit, E-/Live-Casting-Situationen, Camera-Acting etc. Au√üerdem erhalten die Teilnehmenden alle wichtigen Informationen rund um das Thema "Selbstmarketing" - zusammen mit wertvollen Tipps und Tricks. 

Zus√§tzlich produzieren wir eine professionelle SHOWREELSZENE f√ºr jeden Teilnehmenden, welche wir in dem 6-t√§gigen Workshop vorbereiten (*WICHTIGE INFO: Die Produktion der Szenen findet au√üerhalb des Workshops statt. Die Termine werden im Anschluss individuell vereinbart!). des Weiteren erh√§lt jeder Teilnehmende ein kurzes "ABOUT ME", welches wir ebenfalls aufzeichnen werden. 

*Sollte f√ºr den Showreelszene eine erneute Anreise aus anderen St√§dten notwendig sein, werden die Fahrtkosten √ºbernommen.

ZIELGRUPPE: QUEREINSTEIGER*INNEN (ohne Ausbildung - unerfahren oder mit ersten Dreherfahrungen) sowie SCHAUSPIELSCH√úLER*INNEN, die ihre Ausbildung aktuell noch nicht abschlie√üen bzw. abgeschlossen haben.

INFOS & ANMELDUNG √ºber folgenden Link: [https://www.agentur-engelspost.de/workshops-coachings/workshops-und-weiterbildungen/schauspiel-workshop-quereinsteiger-innen-readyforacting/](https://www.agentur-engelspost.de/workshops-coachings/workshops-und-weiterbildungen/schauspiel-workshop-quereinsteiger-innen-readyforacting/)

Filming will commence on the 9th & 11th of December in Stoke-on-Trent

items.text: New to this group and would love to follow my dream of becoming an actor, what are my chances, im 41 years old of an athletic build, English and fluent in Spanish, have experience in mixed martial arts, south east accent but can also do a multitude of accents too, any tips advice would be much appreciated.

topComments.text: Join a local Amateur Dramatics society to find out if you CAN act, as it is a talent that not everyone possesses.  Then, if you‚Äôre any good, get some professional training, a show reel, good headshots and apply to lots of agents for representation.

I started my acting journey at 50. After some extra work, i realised wanted speaking parts, so I i auditioned for a screen acting course - as I wanted feedback/coaching. I then got professional headshos and started with setting up a profile on Mandy, for me unpaid student films were a great training ground and I also got paid work for social media adverts. From there i expanded onto Backstage, Star Now and Talent Talks. The paid work I got booked for enabled me to get onto Spotlight and get an agent. All little steps towards my dream. Lots of learning on the way, such as how to self tape. Good luck

Hello everyone, my name is Jacob Carter, I'm represented by Model and Talent Management, and I'm a starting up actor. I'm 28 years old, I live in Nashville, Tennessee and looking to really become a professional actor and voice over artist.

I have played as a Scare performer in the Terror Trail Haunted Hayride, and played as a background graduate in an upcoming movie. 

Got to go to the Dallas ITA EXPO this November and can't wait to get more projects under my belt. I would love to do business with anyone. Thank you very much

the wait is over! we are now accepting submissions for our summer production of ‚ÄúBe More Chill!‚Äù

for full details, visit the link in our bio.

Simone Nathalia - Director/Choreographer
Taylor McKee - Music Director
Madison Raybould - Choreographer
Morgan Da Silva-Rolph - Stage Manager

Music and Lyrics by Joe Iconis
Book by Joe Tracz
Based on the Novel by Ned Vizzini

audition dates
in-person: December 20th & 21st, 2025
callbacks: January 3rd, 2026
self-tapes: submissions due on Dec. 19th

audition venue:
Carousel Theatre for Young People, 1411 Cartwright St, Granville Island

audition requirements:
all roles in this production are volunteer, non-union. xoxo welcomes performers 18+ of all genders, ethnicities, and skill levels to audition.

what to prepare:
1. 2 contrasting musical theatre songs, (you may only be asked to sing one, but please have both ready).

2. a 1-2 minute contemporary, comedic monologue - this must be memorized.

how to apply:
please email your headshot and resume to theatre@xoxotv.ca to be scheduled with an audition time, or to request a self-tape submission.

character breakdowns can be found in our ‚Äúaudition package‚Äù link in bio.

production dates:
July 15th - 18th, 2026

production venue:
Firehall Arts Centre, 280 E Cordova St, Vancouver

notes:
rehearsals will begin April 30th, 2026
Saturdays 10:00am to 6:00pm
Tuesdays & Thursdays 6:00pm to 10:00pm

contact info@xoxotv.ca or DM us with any questions!

best of luck to all performers - we‚Äôll see you at auditions! üòÅüíÑüêæ

**CASTING CALL **

**Durchgehende Hauptrolle** f√ºr Social-Media-Comedy-Serie **‚ÄûCall Me Barista‚Äú **gesucht!

**Rolle: MIA (w)**

**Spielalter: 20‚Äì25 Jahre**

**Wohnort: Berlin**

Mia ist neu im Team eines hippen Berliner Coffeeshops und versucht zwischen Berliner Schnauze, Hipstern und Selbstzweifeln ihren Platz zu finden. Mia ist nat√ºrlich, nahbar, und beobachtungsscharf.

Die Rolle verlangt pr√§zises Comedy-Timing, schnelles Umschalten zwischen Fassade und echter Emotion, sowie Lust auf ein bisschen Improvisation am Set.

Da wir die Figuren im Writers Room an die Schauspieler*innen anpassen wollen, suchen wir schon in der Entwicklungsphase nach den Besetzungen f√ºr die wichtigsten Rollen.

Drehzeitraum: ab Mai 2025.

Ein Drehtag pro Woche. Langfristig.

Aktuell leider noch No-Budget, daf√ºr bieten wir eine faire Gewinnbeteiligung, Sichtbarkeit als Schauspielerin auf Social-Media-Plattformen, Laufend neues Showreel-Material, sowie regelm√§√üiges Schauspieltraining am Set mit einem professionellen Team.

Bewerbungen per E-Mail an **callmebarista.serie@gmail.com**

Bitte mit Fotos, Showreel (soweit vorhanden) und gerne auch einem Vorstellungsvideo oder einem Link zur Social-Media-Pr√§senz

Are you merging two households into one? Channel 4 are creating a brand-new property and renovation series with presenter and architect George Clarke, and we want to hear from you! 

We‚Äôre looking for families, couples, relatives or friends who are: 
* Selling one home 
* Renovating another 
* Combining two households into one shared home 

You might be: 
* A parent moving in with your adult children
* A blended family creating a new home together
* Moving in with your partner
* Downsizing after a life change
* Preparing a house that will fit everyone‚Äôs needs 

We'd love to hear your story! 

The series follows the renovation, the decisions, the emotions and - ultimately - the reveal of the brand-new home. 

Along the way, you‚Äôll have support and practical tips from George Clarke, one of the UK‚Äôs most trusted renovation experts ‚Äì who can help you get the most out of your project. 

For more information and how to apply, head to

[https://www.channel4.com/4viewers/take-part/dream-home](https://www.channel4.com/4viewers/take-part/dream-home)

Please do tag and share!

IWC Media collect, store and use your personal data in accordance with our privacy policy which is available at [https://www.iwcmedia.co.uk/privacy](https://www.iwcmedia.co.uk/privacy)

items.text:
Here's a Sneak Peek.

PROLOGUE ‚Äî SHADOWS AIN‚ÄôT SILENT
Night hangs low over the city like a hood pulled tight.
 Streetlights flicker ‚Äî tired eyes refusing to sleep.
 Somewhere a siren weeps into the dark, echoing a truth nobody admits:
On this block, quiet is never peace.
 Quiet is set-up.
A figure moves through alley steam ‚Äî slow, controlled, like violence wearing sneakers. Cigarette glow pulses like a heartbeat refusing to die. Every corner whispers Marcus Reed‚Äôs name. Not loud. Not proud. Tentative. Afraid.
Up above, a rooftop door cracks open.
 A shadow watches.
 Patient.
 Hungry.
A text vibrates in Marcus‚Äôs pocket.
 Private number.
 No contact picture.
Three words:
 YOU‚ÄôRE NEXT.
Marcus doesn‚Äôt freeze.
 He‚Äôs been next his whole life.
He crushes the cigarette against brick.
 Smoke ghosts away.
 Concrete groans under his boots.
 Somewhere, a window shuts like a secret learning to keep itself.
The block inhales.
Marcus exhales.
Game‚Äôs already started.
Welcome back.

CHAPTER 1 ‚Äì WAREHOUSE SHADOWS
Part 1: Smoke and Steel 
The camera glides low across a warehouse floor slick with oil stains and cigarette butts. Fluorescent lights flicker overhead like they‚Äôre on their last breath. Stacks of cocaine bricks sit wrapped tight in plastic, piled high like cursed treasure.
 The soundtrack hums low: a heavy bass line, thumping slow, like a heartbeat that knows something‚Äôs coming.
 Marcus Reed steps into frame. The glow of his blunt lights his face for half a second‚Äîhard jaw, eyes sharp, smoke curling like whispers.
 Goons move in the background. One seals bags. Another slams diesel truck doors shut. Rifles glint in the half-light.
 ‚ÄúCount it twice,‚Äù Marcus mutters, his voice steady but cold. ‚ÄúLast man that shorted me ain‚Äôt walking no more.‚Äù
 The room stills for a beat. Even the scales seem louder as the numbers flicker green.
 He taps ash, scans rafters, notes the ladder that wasn‚Äôt there yesterday. A fan ticks, off rhythm, like a bad omen with loose screws.
 Camera pushes in on Marcus‚Äôs hands‚Äîscarred, sure, calm like street weather. He doesn‚Äôt blink when a pallet pops; he only shifts his weight and smiles without joy, the smile you practice when danger starts spelling your name in smoke. Tonight.

Part 2: The Silent Weigh-In 
Close-up: hands, rough and scarred, sliding kilo after kilo onto digital scales. Each beep cuts the silence sharper than a blade.
 Marcus circles the table like a director on set. Every move, every breath, he watches.
 ‚ÄúBag tighter,‚Äù he snaps at one goon fumbling with tape. ‚ÄúYou leave air in there, you might as well sign your death certificate.‚Äù
 The man nods fast, sweat running down his temple.
 Overhead shot: crates stacked against the wall. A shadow moves in the rafters. Quick cut‚Äîgone before anyone notices.
 The bass in the soundtrack climbs higher.
 A stopwatch clicks. Numbers glow cold on a wall clock that‚Äôs always three minutes fast; Marcus keeps it that way, likes getting to trouble before trouble gets to him.
 He lifts a brick, squeezes, listens for that soft crunch that tells the truth. It purrs. He nods.
 The camera lingers on a scale drifting a gram, drifting back‚Äîlike it‚Äôs breathing. ‚ÄúSwap it,‚Äù he orders. ‚ÄúBad lungs.‚Äù
 A forklift coughs awake then dies. Somewhere a phone vibrates.
 Marcus inhales, tastes plastic and promise. He holds the exhale, counts, releases slow. The room copies his rhythm without meaning to, and the silence starts carrying his fingerprint. Twice.

Part 3: Tension in the Corners 
Marcus leans against the steel table, smoke curling from his blunt, eyes fixed on his crew.
 ‚ÄúYou all know the rules,‚Äù he says low, each word deliberate. ‚ÄúRespect. Loyalty. No mistakes. One slip, and this whole empire cracks.‚Äù
 One of the younger goons shifts nervously, avoiding Marcus‚Äôs eyes. Another clears his throat like he wants to speak, but doesn‚Äôt.
 Camera angle: close on Marcus‚Äôs eyes narrowing. A slow zoom, suspicion tightening.
 He taps ash onto the floor. ‚ÄúSay what‚Äôs on your chest, or get out my sight.‚Äù
 The soundtrack drops into silence‚Äîlike the block holding its breath.
 In the corner, a fan chops the air into thin slices. A fly rides the blade, makes a tiny halo, vanishes.
 The kid with the nervous shoes finally finds words. ‚ÄúNumbers feel heavy tonight,‚Äù he mutters.
 Marcus tilts his head. ‚ÄúHeavy means you ain‚Äôt ready.‚Äù
 The door groans somewhere in the dark, a hinge remembering last winter.
 He nods at Darnell. ‚ÄúCheck the perimeter. Twice.‚Äù
 Darnell moves. The camera follows his shadow to a slit of night beneath the loading bay.
 Marcus turns back to the table, lays palms on cold steel, and the room remembers who taught it to be quiet.

Part 4: The Ambush 
The silence shatters.
 A door creaks. Heavy boots echo on concrete. Then‚Äîbang! The warehouse door bursts open, metal screaming. Red-and-blue flashes spill in like blood across the floor.
 ‚ÄúFEDERAL AGENTS! DON‚ÄôT MOVE!‚Äù
 Camera whips fast: goons scatter. Rifles raised. Cash spilling. Bricks tumbling.
 Marcus doesn‚Äôt flinch. He exhales smoke, slow, calm, even as chaos detonates around him.
 ‚ÄúBurn it!‚Äù he roars.
 One of his men kicks over a barrel. Flames lick high, swallowing kilos, swallowing evidence. Gunfire erupts, ricochets sparking off steel beams.
 Quick cuts‚Äîmuzzle flashes, agents shouting, goons yelling. The scene blurs into pure chaos.
 Sprinklers sputter, cough, give up. The floor becomes a mirror of fire and broken plastic.
 Marcus slides behind a stack, returns three shots, moves left, returns two more.
 Darnell yanks a recruit down by the collar, saves his life and loses his hat.
 A flashbang blooms white; sound folds; everyone forgets their own names for half a breath.
 ‚ÄúSouth exit!‚Äù Marcus barks. A shutter grinds halfway, jams.
 He rips a crowbar from a crate, wedges, levers, curses. Metal screams, then yields.
 ‚ÄúMove!‚Äù he orders, and the camera finds his face through smoke, unblinking, carved from the same steel. Sirens growl closer outside.

Part 5: Betrayal in the Smoke 
Camera: handheld, shaky, pushing through the smoke and bullets.
 Marcus ducks behind crates, gun in hand, eyes scanning.
 Then he sees it‚Äîone of his own, whispering to a man in a suit. An earpiece glints under the flashing lights.
 A CI.
 Marcus‚Äôs chest tightens, rage burning. He shouts over the gunfire: ‚ÄúYou sold us out!‚Äù
 The traitor freezes, guilt flashing across his face for a second before he bolts for the exit.
 Marcus fires‚Äîthe shot echoes louder than the others, cutting through the chaos.
 The camera zooms on Marcus‚Äôs face, jaw clenched, smoke and fire swirling around him.
 Voiceover, gritty: ‚ÄúOn the block‚Ä¶ survival don‚Äôt mean living. It means killing what‚Äôs killing you.‚Äù
 The CI stumbles, grabs a pillar, leaves a red handprint like a signature he can‚Äôt take back.
 Agents surge; somebody yells ‚ÄúClear!‚Äù too early and eats a ricochet.
 Marcus pivots, empties the mag, swaps, breath.
 He points at the burning stacks. ‚ÄúLet it all die,‚Äù he orders.
 Darnell nods, eyes hard, herds two soldiers through the gap in the shutter.
 Marcus backs toward the darkness, smoke wrapping him like a cape.
 The screen smears to black as alarms scream, and the warehouse forgets their names.

Close-up: hands, rough and scarred, sliding kilo after kilo onto digital scales. Each beep cuts the silence sharper than a blade.
 Marcus circles the table like a director on set. Every move, every breath, he watches.
 ‚ÄúBag tighter,‚Äù he snaps at one goon fumbling with tape. ‚ÄúYou leave air in there, you might as well sign your death certificate.‚Äù
 The man nods fast, sweat running down his temple.
 Overhead shot: crates stacked against the wall. A shadow moves in the rafters. Quick cut‚Äîgone before anyone notices.
 The bass in the soundtrack climbs higher.
 A stopwatch clicks. Numbers glow cold on a wall clock that‚Äôs always three minutes fast; Marcus keeps it that way, likes getting to trouble before trouble gets to him.
 He lifts a brick, squeezes, listens for that soft crunch that tells the truth. It purrs. He nods.
 The camera lingers on a scale drifting a gram, drifting back‚Äîlike it‚Äôs breathing. ‚ÄúSwap it,‚Äù he orders. ‚ÄúBad lungs.‚Äù
 A forklift coughs awake then dies. Somewhere a phone vibrates.
 Marcus inhales, tastes plastic and promise. He holds the exhale, counts, releases slow. The room copies his rhythm without meaning to, and the silence starts carrying his fingerprint. Twice.

Part 3: Tension in the Corners 
Marcus leans against the steel table, smoke curling from his blunt, eyes fixed on his crew.
 ‚ÄúYou all know the rules,‚Äù he says low, each word deliberate. ‚ÄúRespect. Loyalty. No mistakes. One slip, and this whole empire cracks.‚Äù
 One of the younger goons shifts nervously, avoiding Marcus‚Äôs eyes. Another clears his throat like he wants to speak, but doesn‚Äôt.
 Camera angle: close on Marcus‚Äôs eyes narrowing. A slow zoom, suspicion tightening.
 He taps ash onto the floor. ‚ÄúSay what‚Äôs on your chest, or get out my sight.‚Äù
 The soundtrack drops into silence‚Äîlike the block holding its breath.
 In the corner, a fan chops the air into thin slices. A fly rides the blade, makes a tiny halo, vanishes.
 The kid with the nervous shoes finally finds words. ‚ÄúNumbers feel heavy tonight,‚Äù he mutters.
 Marcus tilts his head. ‚ÄúHeavy means you ain‚Äôt ready.‚Äù
 The door groans somewhere in the dark, a hinge remembering last winter.
 He nods at Darnell. ‚ÄúCheck the perimeter. Twice.‚Äù
 Darnell moves. The camera follows his shadow to a slit of night beneath the loading bay.
 Marcus turns back to the table, lays palms on cold steel, and the room remembers who taught it to be quiet.

Part 4: The Ambush 
The silence shatters.
 A door creaks. Heavy boots echo on concrete. Then‚Äîbang! The warehouse door bursts open, metal screaming. Red-and-blue flashes spill in like blood across the floor.
 ‚ÄúFEDERAL AGENTS! DON‚ÄôT MOVE!‚Äù
 Camera whips fast: goons scatter. Rifles raised. Cash spilling. Bricks tumbling.
 Marcus doesn‚Äôt flinch. He exhales smoke, slow, calm, even as chaos detonates around him.
 ‚ÄúBurn it!‚Äù he roars.
 One of his men kicks over a barrel. Flames lick high, swallowing kilos, swallowing evidence. Gunfire erupts, ricochets sparking off steel beams.
 Quick cuts‚Äîmuzzle flashes, agents shouting, goons yelling. The scene blurs into pure chaos.
 Sprinklers sputter, cough, give up. The floor becomes a mirror of fire and broken plastic.
 Marcus slides behind a stack, returns three shots, moves left, returns two more.
 Darnell yanks a recruit down by the collar, saves his life and loses his hat.
 A flashbang blooms white; sound folds; everyone forgets their own names for half a breath.
 ‚ÄúSouth exit!‚Äù Marcus barks. A shutter grinds halfway, jams.
 He rips a crowbar from a crate, wedges, levers, curses. Metal screams, then yields.
 ‚ÄúMove!‚Äù he orders, and the camera finds his face through smoke, unblinking, carved from the same steel. Sirens growl closer outside.

Part 5: Betrayal in the Smoke 
Camera: handheld, shaky, pushing through the smoke and bullets.
 Marcus ducks behind crates, gun in hand, eyes scanning.
 Then he sees it‚Äîone of his own, whispering to a man in a suit. An earpiece glints under the flashing lights.
 A CI.
 Marcus‚Äôs chest tightens, rage burning. He shouts over the gunfire: ‚ÄúYou sold us out!‚Äù
 The traitor freezes, guilt flashing across his face for a second before he bolts for the exit.
 Marcus fires‚Äîthe shot echoes louder than the others, cutting through the chaos.
 The camera zooms on Marcus‚Äôs face, jaw clenched, smoke and fire swirling around him.
 Voiceover, gritty: ‚ÄúOn the block‚Ä¶ survival don‚Äôt mean living. It means killing what‚Äôs killing you.‚Äù
 The CI stumbles, grabs a pillar, leaves a red handprint like a signature he can‚Äôt take back.
 Agents surge; somebody yells ‚ÄúClear!‚Äù too early and eats a ricochet.
 Marcus pivots, empties the mag, swaps, breath.
 He points at the burning stacks. ‚ÄúLet it all die,‚Äù he orders.
 Darnell nods, eyes hard, herds two soldiers through the gap in the shutter.
 Marcus backs toward the darkness, smoke wrapping him like a cape.
 The screen smears to black as alarms scream, and the warehouse forgets their names.

HAPPY FRIDAY!

Here's a few creative reminders!

-The last Filmmaker Social of the year, hosted by Tricky Ink Productions at True West Film Center in Healdsburg, will be FRIDAY, DECEMBER 19TH, 6-9PM! ONE WEEK FROM TODAY! However! If you're unable to make it to this event, but you want updates on future events, email me and I'll add you to the mailing list!

[https://truewestfilmcenter.org/show/filmmaker-social-5/](https://truewestfilmcenter.org/show/filmmaker-social-5/)

-I have an actor database, and offer casting services to Directors and Producers.

-I run a Discord server for filmmakers and actors that is very active! There are channels for job posting, casting calls, events, and networking!

-I have a lot of projects and efforts planned for the new year! Filmmaking Workshops in Santa Rosa. A feature film in Petaluma. Short films all over the Bay Area. And more!

If you're an ACTOR looking for more work, a WRITER with a short script, an industry veteran looking to host a workshop, a PRODUCER looking to support a project, or a STUDENT just starting off, reach out! Let's bring more work to the Bay Area in 2026!

[Mhamlee.ac@gmail.com](mailto:Mhamlee.ac@gmail.com)

Here's a Sneak Peek.

PROLOGUE ‚Äî SHADOWS AIN‚ÄôT SILENT
Night hangs low over the city like a hood pulled tight.
 Streetlights flicker ‚Äî tired eyes refusing to sleep.
 Somewhere a siren weeps into the dark, echoing a truth nobody admits:
On this block, quiet is never peace.
 Quiet is set-up.
A figure moves through alley steam ‚Äî slow, controlled, like violence wearing sneakers. Cigarette glow pulses like a heartbeat refusing to die. Every corner whispers Marcus Reed‚Äôs name. Not loud. Not proud. Tentative. Afraid.
Up above, a rooftop door cracks open.
 A shadow watches.
 Patient.
 Hungry.
A text vibrates in Marcus‚Äôs pocket.
 Private number.
 No contact picture.
Three words:
 YOU‚ÄôRE NEXT.
Marcus doesn‚Äôt freeze.
 He‚Äôs been next his whole life.
He crushes the cigarette against brick.
 Smoke ghosts away.
 Concrete groans under his boots.
 Somewhere, a window shuts like a secret learning to keep itself.
The block inhales.
Marcus exhales.
Game‚Äôs already started.
Welcome back.

CHAPTER 1 ‚Äì WAREHOUSE SHADOWS
Part 1: Smoke and Steel 
The camera glides low across a warehouse floor slick with oil stains and cigarette butts. Fluorescent lights flicker overhead like they‚Äôre on their last breath. Stacks of cocaine bricks sit wrapped tight in plastic, piled high like cursed treasure.
 The soundtrack hums low: a heavy bass line, thumping slow, like a heartbeat that knows something‚Äôs coming.
 Marcus Reed steps into frame. The glow of his blunt lights his face for half a second‚Äîhard jaw, eyes sharp, smoke curling like whispers.
 Goons move in the background. One seals bags. Another slams diesel truck doors shut. Rifles glint in the half-light.
 ‚ÄúCount it twice,‚Äù Marcus mutters, his voice steady but cold. ‚ÄúLast man that shorted me ain‚Äôt walking no more.‚Äù
 The room stills for a beat. Even the scales seem louder as the numbers flicker green.
 He taps ash, scans rafters, notes the ladder that wasn‚Äôt there yesterday. A fan ticks, off rhythm, like a bad omen with loose screws.
 Camera pushes in on Marcus‚Äôs hands‚Äîscarred, sure, calm like street weather. He doesn‚Äôt blink when a pallet pops; he only shifts his weight and smiles without joy, the smile you practice when danger starts spelling your name in smoke. Tonight.

 The bass in the soundtrack climbs higher.

 The camera lingers on a scale drifting a gram, drifting back‚Äîlike it‚Äôs breathing. ‚ÄúSwap it,‚Äù he orders. ‚ÄúBad lungs.‚Äù
 A forklift coughs awake then dies. Somewhere a phone vibrates.

Marcus leans against the steel table, smoke curling from his blunt, eyes fixed on his crew.

 One of the younger goons shifts nervously, avoiding Marcus‚Äôs eyes. Another clears his throat like he wants to speak, but doesn‚Äôt.

 He taps ash onto the floor. ‚ÄúSay what‚Äôs on your chest, or get out my sight.‚Äù
 The soundtrack drops into silence‚Äîlike the block holding its breath.
 In the corner, a fan chops the air into thin slices. A fly rides the blade, makes a tiny halo, vanishes.
 The kid with the nervous shoes finally finds words. ‚ÄúNumbers feel heavy tonight,‚Äù he mutters.
 Marcus tilts his head. ‚ÄúHeavy means you ain‚Äôt ready.‚Äù
 The door groans somewhere in the dark, a hinge remembering last winter.
 He nods at Darnell. ‚ÄúCheck the perimeter. Twice.‚Äù
 Darnell moves. The camera follows his shadow to a slit of night beneath the loading bay.

Here's a Sneak Peek.

PROLOGUE ‚Äî SHADOWS AIN‚ÄôT SILENT
Night hangs low over the city like a hood pulled tight.
 Streetlights flicker ‚Äî tired eyes refusing to sleep.
 Somewhere a siren weeps into the dark, echoing a truth nobody admits:
On this block, quiet is never peace.
 Quiet is set-up.
A figure moves through alley steam ‚Äî slow, controlled, like violence wearing sneakers. Cigarette glow pulses like a heartbeat refusing to die. Every corner whispers Marcus Reed‚Äôs name. Not loud. Not proud. Tentative. Afraid.
Up above, a rooftop door cracks open.
 A shadow watches.
 Patient.
 Hungry.
A text vibrates in Marcus‚Äôs pocket.
 Private number.
 No contact picture.
Three words:
 YOU‚ÄôRE NEXT.
Marcus doesn‚Äôt freeze.
 He‚Äôs been next his whole life.
He crushes the cigarette against brick.
 Smoke ghosts away.
 Concrete groans under his boots.
 Somewhere, a window shuts like a secret learning to keep itself.
The block inhales.
Marcus exhales.
Game‚Äôs already started.
Welcome back.

CHAPTER 1 ‚Äì WAREHOUSE SHADOWS
Part 1: Smoke and Steel 
The camera glides low across a warehouse floor slick with oil stains and cigarette butts. Fluorescent lights flicker overhead like they‚Äôre on their last breath. Stacks of cocaine bricks sit wrapped tight in plastic, piled high like cursed treasure.
 The soundtrack hums low: a heavy bass line, thumping slow, like a heartbeat that knows something‚Äôs coming.
 Marcus Reed steps into frame. The glow of his blunt lights his face for half a second‚Äîhard jaw, eyes sharp, smoke curling like whispers.
 Goons move in the background. One seals bags. Another slams diesel truck doors shut. Rifles glint in the half-light.
 ‚ÄúCount it twice,‚Äù Marcus mutters, his voice steady but cold. ‚ÄúLast man that shorted me ain‚Äôt walking no more.‚Äù
 The room stills for a beat. Even the scales seem louder as the numbers flicker green.
 He taps ash, scans rafters, notes the ladder that wasn‚Äôt there yesterday. A fan ticks, off rhythm, like a bad omen with loose screws.
 Camera pushes in on Marcus‚Äôs hands‚Äîscarred, sure, calm like street weather. He doesn‚Äôt blink when a pallet pops; he only shifts his weight and smiles without joy, the smile you practice when danger starts spelling your name in smoke. Tonight.

Part 2: The Silent Weigh-In 
Close-up: hands, rough and scarred, sliding kilo after kilo onto digital scales. Each beep cuts the silence sharper than a blade.
 Marcus circles the table like a director on set. Every move, every breath, he watches.
 ‚ÄúBag tighter,‚Äù he snaps at one goon fumbling with tape. ‚ÄúYou leave air in there, you might as well sign your death certificate.‚Äù
 The man nods fast, sweat running down his temple.
 Overhead shot: crates stacked against the wall. A shadow moves in the rafters. Quick cut‚Äîgone before anyone notices.
 The bass in the soundtrack climbs higher.
 A stopwatch clicks. Numbers glow cold on a wall clock that‚Äôs always three minutes fast; Marcus keeps it that way, likes getting to trouble before trouble gets to him.
 He lifts a brick, squeezes, listens for that soft crunch that tells the truth. It purrs. He nods.
 The camera lingers on a scale drifting a gram, drifting back‚Äîlike it‚Äôs breathing. ‚ÄúSwap it,‚Äù he orders. ‚ÄúBad lungs.‚Äù
 A forklift coughs awake then dies. Somewhere a phone vibrates.
 Marcus inhales, tastes plastic and promise. He holds the exhale, counts, releases slow. The room copies his rhythm without meaning to, and the silence starts carrying his fingerprint. Twice.

Part 3: Tension in the Corners 
Marcus leans against the steel table, smoke curling from his blunt, eyes fixed on his crew.
 ‚ÄúYou all know the rules,‚Äù he says low, each word deliberate. ‚ÄúRespect. Loyalty. No mistakes. One slip, and this whole empire cracks.‚Äù
 One of the younger goons shifts nervously, avoiding Marcus‚Äôs eyes. Another clears his throat like he wants to speak, but doesn‚Äôt.
 Camera angle: close on Marcus‚Äôs eyes narrowing. A slow zoom, suspicion tightening.
 He taps ash onto the floor. ‚ÄúSay what‚Äôs on your chest, or get out my sight.‚Äù
 The soundtrack drops into silence‚Äîlike the block holding its breath.
 In the corner, a fan chops the air into thin slices. A fly rides the blade, makes a tiny halo, vanishes.
 The kid with the nervous shoes finally finds words. ‚ÄúNumbers feel heavy tonight,‚Äù he mutters.
 Marcus tilts his head. ‚ÄúHeavy means you ain‚Äôt ready.‚Äù
 The door groans somewhere in the dark, a hinge remembering last winter.
 He nods at Darnell. ‚ÄúCheck the perimeter. Twice.‚Äù
 Darnell moves. The camera follows his shadow to a slit of night beneath the loading bay.
 Marcus turns back to the table, lays palms on cold steel, and the room remembers who taught it to be quiet.

Part 4: The Ambush 
The silence shatters.
 A door creaks. Heavy boots echo on concrete. Then‚Äîbang! The warehouse door bursts open, metal screaming. Red-and-blue flashes spill in like blood across the floor.
 ‚ÄúFEDERAL AGENTS! DON‚ÄôT MOVE!‚Äù
 Camera whips fast: goons scatter. Rifles raised. Cash spilling. Bricks tumbling.
 Marcus doesn‚Äôt flinch. He exhales smoke, slow, calm, even as chaos detonates around him.
 ‚ÄúBurn it!‚Äù he roars.
 One of his men kicks over a barrel. Flames lick high, swallowing kilos, swallowing evidence. Gunfire erupts, ricochets sparking off steel beams.
 Quick cuts‚Äîmuzzle flashes, agents shouting, goons yelling. The scene blurs into pure chaos.
 Sprinklers sputter, cough, give up. The floor becomes a mirror of fire and broken plastic.

 He rips a crowbar from a crate, wedges, levers, curses. Metal screams, then yields.
 ‚ÄúMove!‚Äù he orders, and the camera finds his face through smoke, unblinking, carved from the same steel. Sirens growl closer outside.

Part 5: Betrayal in the Smoke 
Camera: handheld, shaky, pushing through the smoke and bullets.

 Then he sees it‚Äîone of his own, whispering to a man in a suit. An earpiece glints under the flashing lights.

 The traitor freezes, guilt flashing across his face for a second before he bolts for the exit.

 Marcus backs toward the darkness, smoke wrapping him like a cape.

items.text:
PURPLE DREAMS PRODUCTIONS are looking for several performers to join a few projects, primarily our brand new family-friendly play: 

THE PRINCESS & THE KNIGHT

a fantasy play written by Tobias Nicholls

Welcome to Twinklewood, a fantastical land where darkness and light have lived in harmony for decades‚Ä¶ until now.

Whilst the King is away on a royal tour, the Ruler of the Shadow Realm makes an unexpected appearance. Sir Milo is determined to keep his princess safe, but with her Kingdom thrown into chaos, Princess Nova - who has long dreamt of adventure - springs into action, taking them on a journey up to the highest mountain and down to the deepest, darkest cave.

Battles are fought and lessons learned on this funny and exciting quest.  

This brand new production is set to debut at The Seagull Theatre in Lowestoft on Saturday 4th April 2026

Two performances on the one day as a tester before we look at booking any others. 

The script is currently going through a rewrite, with the intention to have the cast help to develop the characters through the rehearsal process with the director. 

Adding to the fantastical nature of the story, the characters of Twinklewood will all feature likenesses to animals - realised through costume and make-up.  Aside from one, roles have not been assigned any particular animal, allowing the chosen actors can help build their character.

Payment: at this stage of development it‚Äôs best to consider this a profit share, although this could change to a flat fee - happy to have open and honest discussions with applicants. 

Rehearsals will take place at our studio in Hunstanton (PE36), and will be as flexible as possible to fit around other commitments.

If you are interested, or know someone that might be, please get in touch via a DM on here, or email purple-dreams@hotmail.co.uk

Battles are fought and lessons learned on this funny and exciting quest.  

This brand new production is set to debut at The Seagull Theatre in Lowestoft on Saturday 4th April 2026

Two performances on the one day as a tester before we look at booking any others. 

The script is currently going through a rewrite, with the intention to have the cast help to develop the characters through the rehearsal process with the director. 

Adding to the fantastical nature of the story, the characters of Twinklewood will all feature likenesses to animals - realised through costume and make-up.  Aside from one, roles have not been assigned any particular animal, allowing the chosen actors can help build their character.

Payment: at this stage of development it‚Äôs best to consider this a profit share, although this could change to a flat fee - happy to have open and honest discussions with applicants. 

Rehearsals will take place at our studio in Hunstanton (PE36), and will be as flexible as possible to fit around other commitments.

If you are interested, or know someone that might be, please get in touch via a DM on here, or email purple-dreams@hotmail.co.uk

**Casting Call for a 20-min short**

Hi everyone! We‚Äôre looking for non-union actors who are based on Vancouver, BC. We're thrilled to have new blood in our team! 

**Production Information: **

-Location: Vancouver, BC

-Shoot Dates: Jan 3rd-4th.

-Genre:Drama, Thriller

-Non-Union/Volunteer

-Crafty+IMDb credit provided 

**Roles: **

**Officer Shaw Male 28-50**

A true believer in justice and law enforcement. He doesn‚Äôt believe mentalism is anything more than cheap party tricks, but he finds Chaz and his shtick entertaining, so he allows Chaz to perform for him and explain himself. With every word Chaz says in his defence, Officer Shaw starts to see through Chaz‚Äôs persona and eventually confronts him about the moral, ethical and legal complications his profession entails. The conversation reaches a boiling point when Chaz attempts to read Officer Shaw‚Äôs mind by repeating the last words spoken to Shaw from his missing daughter.

**Mark Male 28-50**

A bitter, cynical man whose sole goal is to prove that Chaz and everything he stands for is a complete pile of crap. He questions everything, every small movement, every word Chaz says, he does not let anything slip. He is the worst participant a magician could possibly ask for. He believes that Chaz is exploiting people, lying to them about magical abilities in order to profit from manipulating the public‚Äôs belief. Nothing Chaz says or does can change his mind and he will stop at nothing to embarrass Chaz live on air and prove that Chaz is a complete fraud.

**Kayla Female 18-30**

Mark‚Äôs na√Øve podcast co-host. She is fascinated with the idea and concept of mentalism and thinks Chaz‚Äôs persona is incredibly exciting. She represents the average person obsessed with magic and mentalism. She loves tricks being performed on her and believes it‚Äôs all harmless

fun. She doesn‚Äôt see anything wrong with what Chaz is doing and truly believes he can read her mind. She tries to keep the order as Mark and Chaz scream at each other, simply wanting to have a fun time and create an entertaining show for her audience.

**To submit:**

Please submit headshot and demo reel to **theartofreadingminds.short@gmail.com** and indicate which role you‚Äôd like to be considered for.

CASTING CALL ‚Äì ‚ÄúTALE OF TWO‚Äù (SHORT FILM) 

Hey all. I‚Äôm still looking for an older gentlemen for the role of Michael in my upcoming short. 45+ & white presenting. 

Logline:
‚ÄúTale of Two‚Äù is a portrait short film about women‚Äôs strength, focusing on our shared experiences rather than our differences. Through small, intimate scenes, we witness key moments in the lives of two women as they navigate hardship, love, and resilience in parallel journeys.

Production Details:

‚Ä¢ Location: Downtown Vancouver

‚Ä¢ Shoot Dates: 1-3 days ‚Äì end of January

‚Ä¢ Format: MOS (no sync sound) - performances will rely heavily on expressive, facial acting

‚Ä¢ Compensation: Volunteer basis with great meals, greater company, and IMDb credit.

To Submit:
Please send your headshot and CV/demo reel to taleoftwofilm@gmail.com.
Include a slate with your name, age, height, and any unavailable dates.
Submission Deadline: December 6th 4 pm

We are casting for the 2026 Weird and Wonderful festival which will run between March 3rd and March 8th.

‚ÄúSardines‚Äù follows five sardines as they bicker over life's meaning and their purpose in the world. 

We are looking for 5 actors of any age or look who can comfortably play off of each others comedic timing.

If you are interested in auditioning for a role please send a self tape that you feel fits the criteria via we transfer / any other downloadable link to:

Seanrobinsonfreelance@gmail.com

Self tapes are due by 31st December and the cast will be contacted by the new year.

Please note: this is a 20 min play and will be part of a three play evening. A profit share will be paid.

12/12/25

(This Is My) Family (Short Film)

A Comedy about family dynamics

A family near breaking point, implodes in one night. 

Shooting April location TBC

Auditioning: We want to receive self tapes first and those who make it to the next stage, we would love in person auditions by late January of 2026. 

Travel Expenses paid

Student film being screened at The BFI and will be entered into film festivals

Elizabeth (50s-60s) - Narcissistic mother who dominates her kids' lives. She speaks her mind much to the reluctance of everyone around her..

Marie (30s-40s) - She‚Äôs in the middle of a mid-life crisis and she blames elizabeth as she thinks she‚Äôs not the perfect mother that she presents herself as. So Marie rebels against this supposed ‚Äòperfect family‚Äô.

Shaun (30-40s) - Shaun simply accepts his place in the world and has very little self respect. He is in a loveless relationship with his wife (Claire) however he does not rebel against her out of fear of living life alone in his 40s. Yet again every man has his breaking point. 

Clare (30s-40s) - Clare needs power and control, so she has found a man she can excerpt this power on (Shaun.) Clare and Elizabeth are very similar and therefore team up to inflate each other's egos at the expense of Marie and Shaun. 

Email: tylerbrownework@gmail.com for further details

Please only respond if you are based in England as our budget will not cover travel from abroad.

items.text:
‚≠ê OFFICIAL CASTING CALL 

Building a Core Acting Team for a New Film/Stage Universe

I‚Äôm assembling a core long-term team (like Kevin Hart‚Äôs Plastic Cup Boyz / Adam Sandler‚Äôs crew) to develop a new film universe plus multiple original projects.

Phase 1:
A small stage adaptation of my book (just to get everyone in sync).

Phase 2:
We turn that story into our first feature film.

Phase 3 and beyond:
Continuous films inside the Frenchie Extended Universe + original projects outside the universe.
Everyone on the core team will be acting, producing, writing, and helping shape future projects together.

Roles Currently Casting (Core Team Only):

Riley (F) ‚Äì Love interest of the main character. Loyal, grounded, warm energy.

Isabella (F, Puerto Rican) ‚Äì Fierce, supportive, emotional backbone of the group.

Crumbs (M) ‚Äì Comedic timing, lovable troublemaker.

Jordan (M) ‚Äì Serious, loyal, big heart but stern presence.

Marcus (M, Black) ‚Äì Later-series antagonist; charismatic, powerful, intimidating.

Jimmy/Frenchie (M) ‚Äì Already cast.

What I need from you:

Send me a 30‚Äì45 second video reading a short line for the character you‚Äôre interested in.
Nothing fancy ‚Äî I just need to see presence, expression, and vibe.

What this is NOT:

This is NOT a one-off gig or a ‚Äúshow up, get paid, leave‚Äù job.
This is a long-term creative family building something from scratch together.

What this IS:

‚úî A team
‚úî A pipeline
‚úî A chance to grow into acting/producing/directing
‚úî Multiple projects ahead
‚úî Long-term involvement as the universe expands

If you‚Äôre hungry, reliable, and want to build something real ‚Äî comment INTERESTED and I‚Äôll DM you a line to read.

Let‚Äôs build something Buffalo can be proud of. üî•
‚Äî Jimmy

**Casting Certified Fitness, Yoga & Pilates Trainers**
**PAID OPPORTUNITY**

Hello everyone!
I‚Äôm currently looking for **certified trainers** for an upcoming project with **a major activewear brand**. We are preparing a new series of social-media training videos and are now conducting a **preliminary casting**.

We‚Äôre looking for:
‚Ä¢ Fitness / functional training coaches
‚Ä¢ Yoga instructors
‚Ä¢ Pilates instructors
‚Ä¢ Stretching / mobility specialists

We welcome trainers of **different ages and backgrounds**, as long as you are certified, experienced, and confident working with beginner-level clients.

The project includes participation in **on-camera training shoots**.
Details regarding filming dates and compensation will be discussed individually with selected candidates.

If you:
‚Ä¢ hold valid certifications
‚Ä¢ have at least 5 years of teaching experience
‚Ä¢ have on-camera experience (a plus, but not required)
‚Ä¢ are open to collaboration

‚Äî please feel free to **DM me directly**.
When reaching out, include your training specialty and a link to your social media or examples of your teaching.

Looking forward to connecting with talented professionals!

‚Ä¢ have at least 5 years of teaching experience
‚Ä¢ have on-camera experience (a plus, but not required)
‚Ä¢ are open to collaboration

‚Äî please feel free to **DM me directly**.
When reaching out, include your training specialty and a link to your social media or examples of your teaching.

Looking forward to connecting with talented professionals!

CASTING/CREW CALL ‚Äì NEW DOCUMENTARY (Los Angeles, Jan/Feb 2026) 
ÔøΩFrom a TV Producer with Discovery & History Channel credits. 

I‚Äôm currently casting for a new documentary that explores the powerful stories we attach to the objects we treasure most. I‚Äôm looking for people who have one meaningful item something that, when held, brings back emotion, memory, or a story that shaped who you are.

Your object could be:
* A family heirloom
* A gift from someone who has passed
* A reminder of a relationship or life-changing moment
* Or simply something that holds deep, personal significance

This project will highlight everyday people and the extraordinary stories behind the things they hold dear.

FILMING:ÔøΩLos Angeles ‚Äî January & February 2026
If you have an item that carries emotional weight and a story you're willing to share on camera, I‚Äôd love to hear from you.

TO APPLY:ÔøΩPlease get in touch and share a brief description of yourself, your item, and the story behind it. Photos welcome but not required.
Looking forward to hearing your story.

EMAIL: breynolsbri@gmail.com
INSTAGRAM: @bryannareynolds

I am looking for a male actor to play the role of Young Nigel Harrow (AGE 20-23, set in 90s). This is currently as a backup so I have a range of actors to chose. What is required is that I will send over a block of script lasting around 3 minutes each (currently there are 7) and I will need the actor to film these clips in their time and their own environment. Location doesn't matter. This project is unpaid.

If you are interested or have any more questions please drop me an email at Thehollowreturn@outlook.com 

Diolch

Hi everyone!
We‚Äôre currently casting for a fan film titled Becoming Our Spider-Man, and we‚Äôre looking for a talented young actor to play Beck, an important emotional role in the story.

Role: Beck

Age Range: 11‚Äì13

Gender: Female

Character Type: Tough exterior, but dealing with pressure and self-doubt underneath. Beck has a powerful emotional moment with Miles (Spider-Man), where he helps her calm down and feel safe.

We‚Äôre looking for someone with strong emotional range, especially the ability to portray vulnerability in a grounded, realistic way.

About the Scene

Beck‚Äôs storyline is a key moment for Miles‚Äô character. It shows his empathy and responsibility as Spider-Man, and Beck‚Äôs performance helps carry the emotional weight of that moment.
(Everything will be filmed safely, respectfully, and with a guardian present.)

Compensation

Paid role

IMDb credit provided

If you‚Äôre interested in the role Ôøº please send your headshot to my email

 üìß @ppeterb954@gmail.com
Ôøº
(And no for those who are asking this is not a scam)

# **MODEL CASTING CALL-OUT **

**Project:** E-Commerce Shoot ‚Äì Modest Wear Brand

**Category:** Fashion / E-Commerce Modelling

**Compensation:** ¬£250
**Deadline:** Submit Today, Friday, 5th Dec

Hello,

We are casting one female model for an upcoming e-commerce shoot with a modest wear fashion brand. The shoot will focus on a new range of skirt samples.

**Assignment Overview**

This is a clean e-commerce shoot requiring simple, consistent posing. You will be modelling 35 skirt samples, photographed in front, back, and side views.

**Shoot Requirements**

Model will be photographed in 35 skirt looks

For each item, we will capture:

Front View

Back View

Side View

Clean, simple posing suitable for e-commerce

**Model Requirements**

**Height:** 5'9"

**Clothing Size:** UK 8‚Äì10

**Makeup:**

Must do own makeup

Natural beauty look required (clean, fresh, soft glam if preferred)

**Wardrobe to Bring:**

Black and white long-sleeve top

Neutral or simple shoes suitable for e-commerce (flats)

**Preferred Shoot Day**

The client has requested Monday, 8th Dec as the shoot day.

(Please only apply if available.)

**Approx. Duration**

4‚Äì6 hours, depending on workflow and outfit changes.

**Location**

Studio address to be provided once confirmed.

**Experience Required**

E-commerce, lookbook, or showroom experience preferred

Ability to pose consistently and present garments cleanly

Strong posture, neat styling, and reliability

**To Apply**

**Please send:**

Recent digitals or portfolio images

Measurements (height, bust, waist, hips)

Confirm Monday, 8th Dec availability

FRAMEPERFECTPRODUCTION@GMAIL.COM

items.text:
Hi! We are LOOKING FOR A MALE ACTOR for a short film here in Budapest, set during World War II, and we aim to shoot over 2 days in late February 2026 in the H≈±v√∂sv√∂lgy area.

The title for the film is KITART√ÅS. It is a short film set during the Siege of Budapest and is a psychological exploration of the raw emotional cost in war times. The story follows Hungarian soldiers as they face a moral and physical struggle for survival in the last year of the war in Hungary. The role requires fluency in both English (for crew communication/rehearsals) and Hungarian (as the film's dialogue will be in Hungarian).

The short film will be submitted to local and international film festivalsüé¨

This is a low-budget short film, but it will have a symbolic paymentüí∞

We are looking for a person to play one of the lead roles.

√ÅD√ÅM:

Character Description: A Hungarian soldier under Istv√°n‚Äôs command. √Åd√°m is a man torn between obedience to his orders and the stirrings of his own conscience and guilt. His internal conflict becomes a major turning point in the film.

Requirements:

Male, 25‚Äì30 years old.

1.75cm - 1.80cm 

Fit or in a healthy weight

Strong presence

Must speak English and Hungarian fluently

Comfortable performing in outdoor winter conditions.

Strong dramatic ability and emotional range.

If you would like to be considered, please send your headshots, short introduction, and (if available) a showreel or acting CV to:

‚úâÔ∏è contactingdianag@gmail.com

Deadline: 31/12/2025

Kyle
 A seasoned presenter clinging to relevance in a changing media landscape. Desperate for a comeback, he takes one last job‚Äîblinded by ambition, even when the warning signs turn supernatural.

 Kyle‚Äôs loyal second-in-command, tasked with shaping the show‚Äôs content. Often dragged into eerie locations, Spencer must confront whether he‚Äôs valued as a partner‚Äîor just a pawn.

Carla‚Äôs trusted cameraman, now shattered by the night‚Äôs horrors. Haunted and fragile, his trauma slowly pulls him into the house‚Äôs darkness.

sharedPost.text:
Casting call for "People"
We are casting for the 2026 Weird and Wonderful festival which will run between March 3rd and March 8th.

"People" follows Alex (a delivery driver) and his brief encounter delivering fish and chips to a Genie. What will he wish for?

Genie: 

We are looking for a male presenting actor with a playing age of 40-50s. This character needs to be larger than life, think someone that could easily play a jolly Santa Claus. The actor must feel comfortable having a strong command of the stage.

Alex: 

We are looking for a male presenting actor with a playing age in their 20s. The actor playing Alex will also need to have lived experience of living as an LGBT individual and comfortable discussing this struggle on stage.

If you are interested in auditioning for either role please send a self tape that you feel fits the character via we transfer / any other downloadable link to:

sineadrenaye@gmail.com

Self tapes are due by 22nd December and the cast will be contacted by the new year.

Please note: this is a 20 min play and will be part of a three play evening. A profit share will be paid.

Genre: Kom√∂die (Kurzfilm) Laufzeit ca. 8min

Spielalter: Anfang bis Mitte 50

Rollenbeschreibung:

Hauptrolle:

Ein Lehrer in seinen f√ºnfzigern, bereits mit lichtem Haar, klassisch altmodisch gekleidet und eine dazu passende altmodische Einstellung gegen√ºber dem Schulsystem und den Sch√ºlern.

Logline:

Ein unsicherer Lehrer, der vergeblich um Respekt k√§mpft, wird durch den Spott seiner Sch√ºler so radikal ver√§ndert, dass er vom Gutm√ºtigen zum gnadenlos Strengen mutiert.

Nebenrolle:

Sch√ºler:

Spielalter: 18

Ein sensibler und aufmerksamer Sch√ºler, der seinem Lehrer den entscheidenden Rat gibt, damit er von der Klasse respektiert wird.

**Es gibt noch 4 weitere Rollen als Sch√ºlerInnen, je nach Bevorzugung als Komparse oder Nebenrolle mit Text** (bitte nur Bewerber ab 18)

Gage: Low-Budget Projekt, Verpflegung am Set ist vorhanden und Fahrtkosten werden erstattet. Alle Bewerber sollten einen direkten Fahrtweg oder eine selbstst√§ndige M√∂glichkeit zur Unterkunft haben, da diese leider nicht gestellt werden kann.

items.text:
‚ÄºÔ∏è**CASTING CALL**‚ÄºÔ∏è

F√ºr meine Bachelorarbeit suche ich eine Darstellerin f√ºr die Hauptrolle HELENA in einem interaktiven Kurzfilm (Drama).
**Beschreibung:**
Helena befindet sich in einer Phase k√∂rperlicher und geistiger Ersch√∂pfung. Sie versucht, in ihrer Wohnung Hinweise zu finden, die ihre Situation erkl√§ren. 
Die Rolle erfordert eine sehr fein nuancierte Darstellung von innerer Spannung, Orientierungslosigkeit und k√∂rperlicher Schw√§che und das nahezu ohne Dialog und √ºberwiegend in Nah- und Detailaufnahmen.

Der Film ist nicht linear aufgebaut, das bedeutet: die Zuschauer treffen Entscheidungen, die zu unterschiedlichen Szenenverl√§ufen f√ºhren.

**Wo?:** bei 92224 Amberg
**Wann?:** 1 bis 2 Tage im Januar (genaues Datum folgt nach Abstimmung)
**Gage:** Aufwandsentsch√§digung nach Absprache

**Anforderungen:**
Spielalter: ca. 25 bis 40 Jahre alt
starkes nonverbales und k√∂rperliches Ausdrucksspiel

**Bei Interesse bitte einreichen:**
Foto + ggf. Showreel

CASTING CALL (ul√∏nnet)

Til et kortfilmsprojekt med arbejdstitlen ‚ÄúVISIT‚Äù s√∏ger vi 3 skuespillere til b√¶rende roller

FRIDA (Hovedrolle)

MARCEL (Hovedrolle)

Spillealder: 20-28

DEN FREMMEDE (B√¶rende bi-rolle)

Spillealder: 24-30

OM FILMEN:

Frida og Marcel er begge midt i tyverne og er begge p√• hver sin m√•de g√•et i st√• i tilv√¶relsen. Frida f√∏ler, at hun sidder fast i sit ellers billedsk√∏nne og perfekte parforhold, og Marcel er lige blevet dumpet af pigen, han troede var sit livs k√¶rlighed.

I to parallelle handlingsforl√∏b kaster de sig ud i to vidt forskellige fors√∏g p√• at genfinde gnisten i den gr√• tilv√¶relse, p√• to forskellige dates, i to forskellige lejligheder p√• hver sin side af en opgang.

Vi er st√∏ttet af Aarhus Filmv√¶rksted, men er stadig en lavbudget-produktion drevet af passionerede frivillige. Projektet er derfor ikke l√∏nnet, men produktionen d√¶kker transport, samt m√•ltider og forfriskninger p√• set.

üìß Send en mail til [visitkortfilm@gmail.com](mailto:visitkortfilm@gmail.com) med titlen ‚ÄúCasting‚Äù efterfulgt af dit navn.

Vedh√¶ft et vellignende billede og eventuelt showreel/CV eller lignende - s√• kontakter vi dig med mere information.

New dates added - Dec 8-19 in Las Vegas. To book go to https://rebrand.ly/freehdsht

FREE HEADSHOT and 1-HOUR SESSION ‚Äì East Summerlin, Las Vegas

Address sent automatically after booking

Hi! I‚Äôm Steve Fogarty, a Las Vegas headshot specialist and owner of EXPO TRAFFIC, where we run large-scale headshot activations for major trade shows (600-700 people over 2.5 days).

I‚Äôm currently testing new lighting setups and posing flows for upcoming conventions, and I‚Äôm looking for real people to sit for practice sessions in a more relaxed environment. In return for your time, you get a full headshot session and one professional, retouched headshot for free.

**What You Get**
* A 60‚Äì75 minute headshot session
* Multiple looks + lighting setups
* A private online gallery
* One edited, retouched image included
* Additional images optional (zero pressure)

**Examples of my retouching**

[https://rebrand.ly/retouching](https://rebrand.ly/retouching)

Why There‚Äôs a $20 Fee

It‚Äôs not a sales charge. It‚Äôs a **non-refundable security deposit and show-up guarantee** that ensures the schedule stays reliable for both of us. The $20 simply confirms your commitment to attend ‚Äî and your favorite image is still included for free.

How You Get Your Image

After the session:
* We will review your images, and you'll tell me which ones are your favorites that you do not want deleted.
* I will edit and retouch your favorites, then upload them to your private gallery.
* You can download your favorite image using a coupon code (provided).
* You‚Äôre welcome to purchase extras, but it‚Äôs totally optional.

What to Expect / How to Prepare
* Arrive camera-ready (mirror + restroom available)
* Plan for 3‚Äì4 different looks
* Avoid pure white tops if possible
* Relax ‚Äî I‚Äôll guide you through every pose and expression

Safety + Professionalism
* All public areas are video security-monitored for your comfort and safety
* Private areas (bathrooms, changing areas) are never recorded
* References available by request

You can preview my work here:

[https://www.expotraffic.com/headshots/las-vegas-headshots](https://www.expotraffic.com/headshots/las-vegas-headshots)

**Location**

**East Summerlin near Rainbow & Alta**

**Exact address provided after booking.**

**Looking forward to creating something great together!**

**‚Äì Steve Fogarty**

**Owner ‚Äì STEVEN JOSEPH PHOTOGRAPHY | EXPO TRAFFIC HEADSHOTS**
